Hi,

Thanks for the clear responses. What i see is that a theory is a
(parametrized) test inside out; you don&#39;t specify what will work but you
leave out what should not be tested (iow assumptions by leaving out the data
for these cases).

I do indeed like the syntax of theories better than how parameterized tests
should be expressed. Especially using custom annotations @Between
(http://popper.tigris.org/tutorial.html) are very powerful,  also to supply
test data for parametrized tests. 

Anyway the difference between them is clear, perhaps a more expressive
technique for specifying parameter values for a parameterized test will make
it into Junit...

Tx.,

Raphael 



Charlie Poole-2 wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; Hi David,
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; [+CC: Charlie Poole, who might be interested in the example...]
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks - but I&#39;m here too. :-)
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Joakim is correct.  A theory promises that correct code will 
&gt;&gt; pass the theory for any parameters you pass in:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; @Theory public void additionIsCommutative(int x, int y) {
&gt;&gt;    assertEquals(x + y, y + x);
&gt;&gt; }
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; A &quot;Parameterized test&quot; is what I like to call an &quot;answer 
&gt;&gt; key&quot;.  It can be applied to some different parameters, but 
&gt;&gt; you have to look at the key to know which are correct.  If we 
&gt;&gt; converted the Parameterized Runner to behave more like 
&gt;&gt; theories, it might look like (totally making this up):
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; // Read top to bottom
&gt;&gt; @Answers(&quot;a&quot;) public int[] = {3, 4, 5}
&gt;&gt; @Answers(&quot;b&quot;) public int[] = {4, 3, 12}
&gt;&gt; @Answers(&quot;c&quot;) public int[] = {5, 5, 13}
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; @AnswerKey public void pythogoreanTheorem(int a, int b, int c) {
&gt;&gt;    assertEquals(c, hypoteneuse(a, b));
&gt;&gt; }&gt; 
&gt;&gt; The Theories interface currently looks different than the 
&gt;&gt; Parameterized interface because experience with the 
&gt;&gt; Parameterized Runner made me dissatisfied with the interface.
&gt; 
&gt; I think NUnit has some fairly nice syntax for parameterized tests,
&gt; primarily because other people experimented with it first and
&gt; I learned from their experience. So, as payback, here are a few
&gt; alternatives we currently (2.5 Alpha) support...
&gt; 
&gt; [Test]
&gt; public void pythogoreanTheorem(
&gt;     [Values(3,4,5)]  int a,
&gt;     [Values(4,3,12)] int b,
&gt;     [Values(5,5,13)] int c)
&gt; {
&gt;     Assert.AreEqual(c, hypoteneuse(a, b));
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; OR
&gt; 
&gt; [TestCase(3,4,5)]
&gt; [TestCase(4,3,5)]
&gt; [TestCase(4,12,13)]
&gt; public void pythogoreanTheorem(int a, int b, int c)
&gt; {
&gt;     Assert.AreEqual(c, hypoteneuse(a, b));
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; OR
&gt; 
&gt; [TestCase(3,4, Returns=5)]
&gt; [TestCase(4,3, Returns=5)]
&gt; [TestCase(4,12, Returns=13)]
&gt; public void pythogoreanTheorem(int a, int b)
&gt; {
&gt;     return hypoteneuse(a, b);
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; For this particular test, I have a liking for the
&gt; last format. Of course, I&#39;m not sure which of these 
&gt; could be implemented with Java attributes, but I&#39;ll
&gt; leave that for somebody else to figure out. :-)
&gt; 
&gt; Charlie
